\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Have you any id
ea where you might \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Well, I\rquote 
ll put it in the Institute of Education, just because - you know, I have no particular allegiance to this Institution, but there is a library, they do have archives, archivists, and it is central. And I thi
nk, in a sense, now, a national archive seems to be actually less relevant than where things are physically.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Yes.  No, I quite agree.  Okay.  So if we could start with your early life \endash  when you were born and where?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Yes.  Yes.  I was born in 1944, in the middle of the bombing in London.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And did you grow up in \'85 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 London, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Can you tell me a bit about your parents? [cf}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5071929  Ann Oakley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \rquote s account in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Man and Wife}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 , 1996]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, my father [Richard Titmuss] was a self-made universit
y professor.  He was self-made in the sense that he left school at 14, so he had no formal educational qualifications, and he worked in insurance. And that gave him an interest in, essentially, inequalities and health, and why some people died sooner than
 others.  So he did some very pioneering work with a man called Jerry Morris, who died recently at the age of 99\'bd, and I wrote an appreciation of Jerry Morris in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
International Journal of Epidemiology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 .  They formed this sort of partnership during the War
, and they wrote these really pioneering papers on social medicine, using a new approach to the analysis of mortality statistics.  So he built himself a career which was initially in that area. Then he was hired to write one of the volumes of the social h
istory of the war \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Problems }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929 of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643  Social Policy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643  \endash  which, in my view, is his best work, and it earned him a Chair at the London School of Economics.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And at what stage in that career did you come on the scene?  What was he doing when you were born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
I was an inconvenience in the sense that he had to move out of his study (LAUGHS) to accommodate me!  So he was still making his way up.  The year he went to LSE, I was about five or six. I went to a new big school at the same time, and we moved house to 
West London - well, we were living in West London, but we moved to a house then, near my school, and with easy access for him to commute to LSE.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 And your mother?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
My mother was an untrained social worker. Well, she never had any training.  She was a volunteer social worker.  She worked the 1930s in clubs for unemployed men, in London.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
How did she get into that kind of work, do you know?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 I don\rquote 
t know, because my mother, curiously, left very little history of her own life.  She left - my father died in 1973, and she died in 1987, so she had quite a long period in which she was, essentially, pruning and sorting his papers, and her concern was his
 career and not hers, so there\rquote s very little record of actually how she got into things.  There\rquote s no record, for instance, of the schools she went to, and so it\rquote 
s a bit strange.  She came from a very conventional sort of middle-middle-class background, and was clearly a bit of a rebel, because that\rquote 
s what took her into the area of social work with the unemployed, and it was in that context that she met my father.  And she did continue with work a bit after they married, but only for a bit, and then she never
 worked again.  And that was the style of the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Yes. You said that she came from a very middle-middle-class background \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
What about your father, how would you describe his background?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, the official story about my father is that he came from an impoverished rural background, but I don\rquote t think it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643  impoverished, in the sense that they lived in a reasonable house, and he was sent to a small private school.  But the story about his father - who was a farmer originally \endash  was that he didn\rquote 
t do very well, he drank a lot, they moved to London, he set up a business as a haulage contractor, which didn\rquote t do very well, and he died relatively young, leaving my father as the eldest of three children in a responsible position for the family.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Did you know the other grandparents when you were growing up?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 I knew my father
\rquote s mother, and my mother\rquote s mother, and my mother\rquote s father died when I was about six, of stomach cancer.  So I had these two gran
nies, essentially, who were not the sort of grandmother that I am, for instance, (LAUGHS) in that they never took me out, never.  I never went to stay with them.  They were quite distant and quite occupied with their own lives, although they neither of th
em did very much.  I didn\rquote t reflect on it at the time, but I do reflect on it now \endash  as one does \endash  as you go through the experience of having children and grandchildren, and you think, \'93
But what happened to me?  What were my parents, and what were my grandparents doing?\'94 and I think it gives you a different perspective on the whole thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And the maternal grandfather, who died when you were about six, do you know much about his background?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
He worked for a cutlery firm.  He went round the country, 
I suppose selling this cutlery, in the days when that was actually quite a high-status job, and he was quite educated and literate.  I think he spoke French and German. I remember him as a very kind man, and I think my mother was quite close to him.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Okay.  Can you tell me a bit about the school that you went to in West London?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
The school I went to was called Haberdashers\rquote  Aske\rquote s, and it was a direct grant school \endash  that meant it had a grant from the government - so at the age of 11 about a third 
of the places were free, in the sense that the people who passed the 11+ didn\rquote t have to pay.  My mother sent me there \endash  and it was my mother\rquote s idea \endash 
 when I was six, so they paid for me at this school from 6-11, and then much to their surprise, because, apparently, they didn\rquote 
t think that I would pass the 11+, I did, and I stayed there until I was 16. But I absolutely hated the School.  It was a girls\rquote  school, it was very conventional, you weren\rquote t allowed to have opinions of your own, it was terribly regulat
ed, and I was really quite unhappy there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Can you remember what sort of expectations they had of what girls would do when they left school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
(LAUGHS) No! I mean, I think the whole of my form
al education was very unclear about what it was that women were supposed to do.  On the one hand, obviously women were supposed to be educated, but on the other hand, they were supposed to be wives and mothers, and this was what was never explained, was h
ow you were supposed to do both!  (LAUGHS)  So my school was quite academic.  Interestingly, I\rquote ve stayed in touch with a few people, and most of them have done very little with their lives.  I don\rquote 
t think the school produced any pioneers of any sort.  I left at 16, and then I just absolutely refused to go back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
How did your parents react to that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Badly!  But I said I wasn\rquote t dropping out of education, I said I wanted to do my \lquote A\rquote  Levels, and I wanted to go to university. I decided I wanted to go t
o Oxford, and the School said I had absolutely no chance of ever making it.  So my parents did, I think, wisely say, \'93Well, if you can find somewhere else to go and do your \lquote A\rquote  Levels, then that\rquote s all right\'94
.  So in those days, there were these things called \'93Polytechnics\'94, so I went to Chiswick Polytechnic where I did \lquote A\rquote 
 Levels, and where I was in the company of a much more diverse group of students, some of whom were in their mid-twenties or older.  And some of them were men.  I mean, I\rquote d been at an all girls\rquote 
 school, I had no brothers, it was a very small - I mean, we had no extended family, so I had no male contact.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And two grandmothers!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
What?  Yes, two grandmothers!  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
So what was it like, going to the Poly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 It was absolutely won
derful.  But one of the reasons it was wonderful was that the classes were very small and the teaching was very good.  We had a French teacher who - I developed this passion for French literature, and he just gave me all these books to read, and saw me af
ter school, and talked to me about French literature.  It was completely, completely a different atmosphere and it was very liberating.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Just to go back to the School, did you ever talk with any of your friends at that School about what they were hoping to do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Any idea why those conversations didn\rquote t happen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
No.  (LAUGHS)  No.  I mean, it was a long time ago!  And it was a very high pressure environment in the sense that we had to take the school exams twice a year, and everything w
as graded, and all the marks were read out at the end of term, and there were something like 600 girls there, so we had to sit on the floor, cross-legged, with splinters in our bottoms, listening to the marks of all these 600 girls being read out!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 So very competitive?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Yes.  And I was no good at sports, and it was one of those places where you were supposed to be interested. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
You say it was quite academic, was there an expectation that girls would go on to university, do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Yes.  But I can remember my Headmistress, who was a very strange woman, saying nobody was to go to the London School of Economics because it was a hotbed of Socialism, which it had been, but wasn\rquote t any more \endash 
 and that was where my father was teaching, so I thought that was very strange.  So, I don\rquote t know where you were supposed to go - Manchester, or Birmingham? There wasn\rquote 
t a sense of the girls at that school reaching out and trying to do ambitious and difficult things, or unusual things.  One of my strongest memories is of an English class/lesson, in which I wrote an essay about Jane Austen - I didn\rquote 
t like Jane Austen, and I said so, and the English teacher said, \'93You are not allowed to have this opinion.  Everybody has to like Jane Austen\'94.  (LAUGHS)  I\rquote ve never read Jane Austen since!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And you said you wanted to go to Oxford. Where did the idea of going to Oxford come from?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
I think it actually came from my father.  Neither of my parents had been to university, and I think they cherished a not too secret ambition that their only daughter would make up for the things that they hadn\rquote t achieved in this area.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 So talk me thro
ugh, what was it like going to Oxford, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, looking back on it, I shouldn\rquote t have gone to Oxford, in a sense.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Why is that?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5071929 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 I went to do Philosophy, Politics, and Economics, which was the nearest thing to Social Science that you coul
d do then.  And, in fact, in my last year, sociology was introduced as an option on the politics syllabus \endash 
 that was the first time it was taught at Oxford, so that was 1964.  I should probably have gone to LSE or Sussex and done Social Science, but for on
e reason or another I decided... I went to Somerville [1962-5]. Dame Janet Vaughan was the Principal of Somerville, and she\rquote 
s a very very interesting pioneering woman, and she gave a talk on the first day, which was the sort of thing that I never got from my school, which was, \'93You\rquote re important women, and you\rquote re going to do important things\'94
. I found that quite inspiring.  But the actual [work] - I spent the first two terms doing symbolic logic, for instance: actually, I think doing symbolic logic is a very good training in how to think, but I didn\rquote 
t think so at the time.  I did moral philosophy, general philosophy, political institutions, and it was a strange degree, and I think, in some ways, it still is, and there was very little connection between the su
bjects.  And certainly when I started to do sociology in the last ye}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid10768769 ar there was no attempt to link}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
 from that area into the others.  I spent some time doing a kind of analysis of all the examples in the Oxford moral philosophy literature, all the examples 
that people gave, and they were all incredibly upper-class.  (LAUGHS)  But nobody was very interested in that at the time.  But yeah, as a social experience, Oxford in those days, the ratio of men to women was seven or eight to one. It was a very beautifu
l place, aesthetically I had a very good time.  Politically, I joined everything.  I didn\rquote t do a tremendous amount of work.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6309058 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And the friends you had at the time when you were at Oxford, what sorts of things were they thinking about going on and doing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 I don\rquote 
t remember much discussion about these wonderful careers that people were going to have.  There was great preoccupation with men, and a general expectation that one would be a failure if one didn\rquote t leave Oxford with a husband, or a fianc\'e9.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 And in your case?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, I did actually get married in the middle of my third year. And now, I think one of the motivations was to escape my parents, because at that time, in the sixties, that was the orthodox way of liberating yourself from your fa
mily of origin - as a woman. The idea of going and living on your own when you were 20 or 21, that wouldn\rquote t have been allowed, so to speak.  And I hated the name \'93Titmuss\'94,  I hated it.
\par  
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Why?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, I was bullied a lot - I say \'93bullied\'94, it wasn\rquote t a word I used then, but teased a lot. It\rquote s not a very nice surname to have, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
I never thought of that!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
No.  And I just hated it.  I\rquote m being very cynical about it.  I did fall in love, and I did want to have children.  I was very conscious of the disadvantages of being an only child of ageing parents \endash 
 well, my mother was 41 when I was born, my father was a bit younger \endash  and I only remember my mother with grey hair and not very much energy.  And I don\rquote 
t know to what extent all this was conscious. Some of it may be a reconstruction. But I didn\rquote t want to repeat that pattern.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
So you left Oxford a married woman.  And what did you do then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
I did various bits of research to earn money.  I worked for Tosco Fyvel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 you know, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Insecure Offenders}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
 [1961], I did some research for him on higher education.  He was actually the father of a very close friend of mine at Oxford, and he was also the father of a woman called Hannah Gavron, who you may have heard of? Who wrote, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Captive Wife}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643  [1966] which was regarded as a sort of predecessor to my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Sociology of Housework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643  [1974]. Hannah did that as a Ph.D. student at Bedford College, which i
s where I was.  But she killed herself shortly before the book was published. It\rquote s relevant, in a number of ways, to my life at the moment, in the sense that I\rquote m in touch with one of her sons who doesn\rquote 
t remember her, who is trying to reconstruct the story of his mother, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Captive Wife}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
 was a book that was extremely important at the time.  How did we get on to Hannah Gavron?  What was the question?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
I asked you what you did after you left.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Oh, right.  So I did some work for Tosco Fyvel, and I did a project for the University of Leeds on what was called \'93The Teaching of Immigrant Children\'94
. I toured schools in West London, talking to teachers, particularly head teachers, about their management of intakes of children who couldn\rquote t speak English,
 because at the time there was a big hoo-hah about the fact that these children were actually being put in separate classes, but it wasn\rquote t kind of officially acknowledged.  So I was thrown in at the deep end, you know!  I was 21 and (LAUGHS) didn
\rquote t know very much about the world, and I was turning up in these really rough schools in Southall, and asking insolent questions of the head teachers. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
How did you get into research though?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10768769 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Well, in my last year at Oxford, I did these two new papers in sociology.  One I think was called \'93
Modern Social Institutions\'94, and the other one was \'93Sociological Theory\'94.  Sociological Theory was taught by a man called Bryan Wilson, who famously wrote a book called, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Sects and Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 , and didn\rquote 
t understand why people thought that was a funny title. He used to cancel my tutorials when he had to go and do the All Souls wine tasting.  And he always called me \'93Miss Titmuss\'94.  So I wasn\rquote t very inspired by him.
  But I was very inspired by Chelly Halsey who taught the other paper. I mean, he just opened my eyes. I remember going to tutorials with him in Nuffield College, which, of course, was a different place from the other colleges, and just suddenly realising
 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid10768769  this is what I wanted to do.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
So when I left Oxford, I think I had probably three ambitions.  One was to have some children; one was to do social research; and one was to write novels.  I had always wanted to be a writer, and from the age of five or s
ix had scribbled things, and thought, \'93When I grow up, I\rquote m going to write novels and poems\'94
. So I wrote a couple of novels after I left Oxford, and one of them was accepted by a publisher who then changed his mind when he saw the second novel, because he s
aid this proved that I was a one-novel person. I never quite recovered from that.  I mean, they weren\rquote 
t exceptional novels, but they were in the Margaret Drabble first novel tradition.  They were pretty much on a par, so they might have got published \endash  and then my li}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid10768769 
fe might have been different.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
But I decided, then, having done these various bits of research, and then I did some work, not for the Institute of Community Studies, but for the Institute of Social Studies in Medical Care, which was in the basem
ent of the Institute of Community Studies, run by Ann Cartwright, and I did some interviewing for her.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6309058 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Can you digress slightly, you said you were really thrown in at the deep end.  Tell me a bit about that. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, like many social scientists of that time, I had very little training \endash  there wasn\rquote t a training.  One made it up as one went along!  This isn\rquote t a digression, it\rquote s relevant \endash  at the moment I\rquote 
m writing a biography of somebody called Barbara Wootton, and there is a lovely account of her standing up at some conference in the 1950s \endash  it\rquote s in somebody\rquote s autobiography, I can\rquote t remember who - oh yes, Norbert Elias \-
- and Barbara Wootton says to everybody, \'93Well, you know, none of you are sociologists, you\rquote ve all come from somewhere else\'94. Which
 is true, we had all come from somewhere else, in the sense that we had often had backgrounds in other subjects, and sociology/social science was being made, in an important sense really, as an academic discipline at that time.  So if you were out there, 
and you were embarking on an interviewing project, or a whatever project, you hadn\rquote t done a research methods training course, you hadn\rquote t done a training in how to interview, you just went and did it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And if we could, at this moment, move on to the Ph.D. How did you come to sign up for a Ph.D.?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16611987 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Oh well, I have told this story in various places. I signed up for the Ph.D. in 1969.  I had my first two children in 1967 and 1968. A boy and a girl. And we were living in West London, and Robin was teaching at Bedford College \endash 
 teaching sociology at Bedford College \endash  and I was pretty much a full-time mother, although I was always trying to do something else.  I wrote some scripts of children\rquote s television, I did some very tedious work for some catalogue of 
businesses in the East End, which involved me sitting in the playpen to make the phone calls, and giving the children the run of the house \endash 
 it was the only way I could do it!  I was quite isolated because I was the first of my friends to have children, and in those days it was much more difficult, there weren\rquote 
t these networks of young mothers that you could plug into, so I think I was probably quite lonely.  I, of course, got a diagnosis of post-natal depression and was put on various anti-depressants and 
it was a difficult period. It was nothing to do with my feeli}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16611987 ngs about my children at all.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Of course, a lot of my work, subsequently, has interrogated this whole notion of post-natal depression, which most of the time is actually a label for women who are
 chronically exhausted and sleep-deprived, and just have too much to do, and I think that was probably my situation.  But I remember there being a sort of conversion moment when I was dusting bookshelves in Robin\rquote 
s study and found these books on the sociology of work, and I thought, \'93What I\rquote m doing is work\'94
.  And I looked in these books, and I looked in the index of various books, and there was nothing about housework.  There were quite a few references to the fact that employed women\rquote s orientation to their
 employment work was always different because their primary commitments were to the home.  And I thought, \'93Well, what I am doing here, which is looking after children and cleaning houses, would be paid work.  So why is it that this whole area of women
\rquote s labour is completely missing?\'94
  So I decided I wanted to do a study of housework, and I registered at Bedford College and spent quite a long time trying to find a supervisor who understood what I was trying to do, and I completely failed. My supervisor never
 understood what I was trying to do, at all.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6309058 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Because I know you
\rquote ve written about how people, at that time, thought the choice of topic was \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, it was bizarre!  Completely bizarre, you know!  The framework for my Ph.D. was, \'93Let\rquote s look at housework as work, not as an aspect of the feminine role\'94
, but in the same way that people like Robert Blauner had looked at the circumstances of factory work and the ways in which the conditions of factory work are quite alienating for the worke
r. I used some of the questions that he asked about monotony and excessive pace, that he asked the factory workers \endash  I asked those of housewives in order to make some kind of direct comparison.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
You said that your supervisor never really got it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
So how did that work in terms of any kind of support for you, what you were doing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, no support.  There wasn\rquote t any support.  There were a couple of other women who were doing Ph.D.s with this supervisor, around the same time, and we formed a little support group of our own.  [...] I had a lot of respect for some my supervisor
\rquote s [...] work, but he was very much - well, first of all he was a misogynist, and secondly, he was very much into measurement. And a combination of those two things
 in our supervisions was quite difficult for me.  And in the end, he used to reduce me to tears, regularly, and he really fought with me about the final stages of the analysis. He used to ring me up at home in the evenings and say, \'93You can\rquote 
t write this\'94, and, \'93You can\rquote t do that\'94, and actually it was harassment, you know?  But there was no culture of - there was no way in which I could understand that at the time. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And so your research design, if you like, in that study, how did you decide? I know you said you wanted to ask some standard questions that you could compare with another, but how did you go about evolving that design?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
A good question!  (LAUGHS)  You know, I very much}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16611987  wanted to get women\rquote s accounts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 . I don\rquote 
t know to what extent my wanting to get women\rquote s accounts was based on any kind of thorough appraisal of the literature at the time.  I just wanted - I felt it was important to listen to women\rquote 
s stories about this, so what I developed was a combination of these very structured questions and very open-ended questions about, you know, \'93Take me through everything that you did yesterday\'94.  And this was done as a Ph.D. \endash 
 I had a Studentship from what was then the Social Science Research Council, I think it was \'a31500 a year, and I spent the wh
ole of it on a babysitter for nine hours a week, and the rest of the Ph. D. I did in the evenings and weekends.  And the grant, I can remember that the grant for married women was less, then, than the grant for married men, and I had a a whole corresponde
nce with the Secretary of State for Education at the time, and a letter from him saying that the reason for this differential was that my husband was supposed to give me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16611987 \'93}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 pocket money\'94.  So my reply to that was, \'93Well, if I send you a letter saying that he won\rquote t give me any pocket money, will you give me the same grant?\'94
  And that was the end of the correspondence.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And they actually used the phrase, \'93pocket money\'94?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Yes.  And the regulations were changed a few years later.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 So when you said y
ou wanted to hear women\rquote s voices and descriptions, saying you had some very open-ended questions, how did [your supervisor] react to the methodology of it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 I think he wasn
\rquote t so critical of what was in the interview schedule, it was more a question of these ratings and assessments and codings that he felt that I needed to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Can you tell me a bit more about what he wanted?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, you know, actual life events and so on. I did some of what he wanted: }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Sociology of Housework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16611987 
 [is full of]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643  chi-squares.  I used to do the chi-squares by hand \endash  I worked out the formula, and worked it all out.  The relevance of the reduced students
hip was that the resources for doing this work \endash  the material resources \endash 
 were very limited, which is one reason why I only did 40 interviews.  I was also very aware that Hannah Gavron had set out to do a hundred interviews, on the grounds that she would n
ot have to calculate any percentages then.  But she stopped at 96 because she got tired.  And I think I stopped at 40 because I seem to remember a methods book by Johann Galtung, which said the minimum number of cases you needed to do chi-squares was 40, 
and I thought, \'93Right!  Well, I\rquote ll do 40!\'94  But, in those days you could get names of people to interview without going to Ethics Committees, so I got the names from two general practices in West London \endash 
 I was just let loose in the files.  I looked up names, and turned up on people\rquote s doorsteps, [with my tape recorder] in a shopping basket.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
