t work all the time, I negotiated, of course. This was something that was happening around the same time - a revised domestic division of labour in which the children\rquote 
s father did actually take responsibility for them one or two days a week.  He got his teaching into three days a week, we ran this terr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid686388 ibly tight kind of timetable.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 And this is also the period when Women\rquote s Liberation arrived in 
Britain, so for the housework interviews I had some questions at the end of the schedule about what people thought of Feminism and Women\rquote s Liberation. So I must have been interested in it then, and one of the women I interviewed said, \'93
Well, I don\rquote t really know, but we\rquote ve got a meeting, next week. There\rquote s a National Housewives Register, and we\rquote ve got a speaker from the Women\rquote s Liberation Workshop coming\'94, so I said, \'93Well, I\rquote 
ll come as an observer\'94.  I remember turning up at this house in Ealing, and the do
or was opened by a woman in hot pants and boots, and the pram was in the hall!  (LAUGHS)  Bizarre!  And they were a couple of American women who were starting this Group in West London, and which I joined, and one of the women is still a friend of mine no
w.  And so that, the experience of being in these small consciousness-raising Groups was an important resource for me, I think.
