\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 I\rquote 
m thinking back - so you did your chi-squares. How did you deal with the more qualitative components of what the women were saying?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, there are quite a lot of quotes in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Sociology of Housework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
, but the history of that book is that I put together this enormous proposal for a whole book on, not just the Ph.D., but the whole history of housework and everything: there were 20 chapters, and I sent it to Penguin
, and it came back with a lot of annotation by a young man in the office.  Basically they rejected it.  So I thought, \'93Well, all right.  I\rquote ll cut it up into two\'94.  So I cut it up into two, and Penguin did a book called, }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Housewife}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643  [1974], and in the middle of that book there were four long interviews with women. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Sociology of Housework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
 was more the academic side of things.  That was done by a small publisher called Martin Robertson. They suggested that I write an introductory chapter about the treatment of women in sociology \endash  which I did \endash 
 and that was a very good idea.  So I raced through Marx and Weber [and Comte and Durkheim], pointing out the ways in which they had not taken women seriously, which was regarded as quite scandalous at the time \endash  this wa
s 1974 the book was published.  The problem was I couldn\rquote t publish the books until I\rquote d got the Ph.D., so it was all rather close timing. So I got the Ph.D., and then published the books the following month, or something like that!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 And how were the bo
oks received by your academic peers?
