Quite well, actually.  There were some really appreciative reviews by people who really appeared to understand what I was trying to do.  There were some negatively critical ones, but I can remember one, and I thin
k it was in a fairly serious journal, and it was by a man, and it was a review of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Sociology of Housework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 , and his only criticism was that there wasn\rquote t much humour in it.  But then, he said, \'93On the other hand, there\rquote s really not much to laugh about in this subject\'94
.  But I took that to heart, and I put humour in all of my subsequent books, because I thought it was a reasonable point!  (LAUGHS)  But they got a lot of publicity, and they got a lot of publicity in the general media as well, and I did a lot
 of interviews. There were a lot of radio interviews and television interviews because, I think, of the timing, you know - Germaine Greer, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Female Eunuch}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 , was slightly earlier [1970], but there were a lot of books [on women coming out].
