Yes.  The point about a systematic review is it\rquote s not like a traditional literature review.  For a traditional literature review, which we\rquote ve all done, you look at your bookshelf, and you
 pull a few books off, and you go to a library and you just select a few pieces, and then you come to an opinion about it all.  But in terms of knowledge accumulation, that is a pretty silly way to go, because you will invariably find, when you really sea
rch the literature in an area, that there is very much more than you thought, and some of it says things that you couldn\rquote 
t possibly imagine.  So, for example, if you want to know what is the effect of standardised assessment tests on kids at school, the bes
t thing to do is to look for the well-designed studies which have actually attempted to measure the impact of these kinds of tests on boys and girls in different types of schools, and to look at all of that literature, and to come to a conclusion on the b
asis of that, rather than just a few studies that you happen to know about, because the few studies that you happen to know about can be tremendously misleading.
