\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
I think it has to do with this whole qualitative/quantitative divide, and the fact that people seem to identify with one or the other, and it\rquote s almost a question of empires!  (LAUGHS)   You\rquote 
re a defender of qualitative research, and this is what you do, and you don\rquote t listen to the people who do what you think of as quantitativ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid10701566 e research, and vice-versa.  It\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 s paradigm warfare, and people build their careers on paradigm warfare, and I don\rquote t think that the point of working in research - in a university or anywhere else 
\endash  is to engage in this sort of warfare with one\rquote 
s colleague.   The point is not exactly to change the world, that would be rather ambitious, but the point is to try and make this connection between the findings of well-conducted research - and that well-conducted research can be research o
f all sorts of different kinds \endash  the point is to try and make connections between that research and the issues that affect people out there.  The standard text of mine, that I have always admired, is Wright Mills, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 The Sociological Imagination}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 , it\rquote s about the connections between the private and the public, and it\rquote 
s about the use of the sociological imagination to make these kinds of bridges between what it is we can find out as researchers, and how it is that we can improve the well-being of people who are supposed to benefit from the policies.
