\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, I think my work has had almost no impact, in a sense, because people continue to talk about the distinction, so I don\rquote 
t know quite what the question is. On a very basic level, qualitative research is engaged in quantitative statements, and vice-versa.  So to me, a good research project is one where you are concerned about issues of representation \endash 
 I mean, have you got a
 representative sample?  For a lot of the systematic reviews that we do, we look at the socio-demographics of people included in studies, and, of course, unsurprisingly, we find that the vast majority of research conducted excludes people who don\rquote 
t speak English, it excludes very poor people, it excludes black people, and yet people generalise on the basis of who they\rquote ve got in these studies, as though they can generalise about the world!  Well, that\rquote 
s ridiculous!  So in all research you need to be concerne
d about the universe of people from whom you have got data, and what it is that you can really say about that universe.  And in all research - I can think of some epidemiological research, and perhaps some kinds of randomised trials in which you wouldn
\rquote t do this, but generally it\rquote s a good idea to listen to what people have to say about their experiences, because if you go in with your presuppositions, you\rquote re not going to know anything more than your presuppositions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Okay.  Can we just stick with this one for a minute, then?  So you\rquote ve argued for randomised controlled trials, I know, quite strongly, in all experimentation \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 There\rquote 
s a difference.  There is a difference.  A lot of research uses [some kind of] experimental method, uses some kind of c
ontrol group or observational study, but we know, from hundreds of reviews that have been done, looking at those kinds of experimental designs on the one hand, and experimental designs which have used the very simple device of random allocation into two d
ifferent groups, that you get bias with the first set of designs and you don\rquote t, on the whole, with the second.  So the advantage - there\rquote 
s nothing very sophisticated or mysterious about it, but the advantage of randomisation is just that you don\rquote t have to d
o any of this complicated regression analysis looking at the impact of this, that and the other. I think I have a very strong pragmatic streak.  This is a very simple device for addressing our responsibility, as researchers, to try and avoid saying things
 that are not reliable about what it is that we\rquote ve found.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Why do you think some people are so resistant to that method?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Well, there is an unfortunate political history about the use of experimentation in some areas of medicine, which has put people off.  There is not such a history in most areas of public policy experimentation, so we need to be discerning.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Yes.  So I suppose what I\rquote m curious about is \endash  I know you don\rquote t want the labels \'93qualitative\'94 and \'93quantitative\'94, but if I could perhaps just talk about methods, then, rather than calling them \'93qualitative\'94 and \'93
quantitative\'94, so where would in-depth interviewing, for example, fit into a randomised controlled trial?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9911662 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 There are now many trials which collect qualitative data from in-de
pth interviews with people in the trial, as a way of not just getting their experiences of being in a trial, but as a way of assessing outcome.  So if you want to know what is the impact of different treatments for breast cancer, prostate cancer, you don
\rquote t only look at, \'93Do people die, or do they develop cancer again?\'94 but you look at what they have to say about their experiences of the different forms of treatment \endash 
 not only on the level of physical symptomatology but some interventions, some forms of treatment mean loads and loads of trips to the hospital, and some of them don\rquote t.  So for people who don\rquote 
t have much money, what does it mean to have to go to the hospital once a week?  You need to ask people these open-ended questions about their experiences, and all of that constitutes part of the assessment of the effectiveness of these treatments.  It
\rquote s not just whether the people die or not.  And actually for most people it\rquote s a matter of negotiating risk.  Some people might prefer to take a higher risk of d
ying in order to avoid some of the very very unpleasant consequences, for example, of some of the drugs that might be used in one method of treatment.  And so we need to know about how people understand and negotiate risk in life.  We do not need to impos
e on them some kind of absolute view about the whole point of life being to do whatever you can to avoid dying.  That isn\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9911662 t actually how people behave!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 You don\rquote t have to do it all with in-depth interviewing.  In some of the trials that we\rquote ve done, we\rquote ve us
ed very detailed open-ended postal questionnaires. You have to offer help for people who need translation, or need help filling them in, but actually, a postal questionnaire can be a qualitative instrument.  The accounts, sometimes, that we\rquote 
ve had written on some of these questionnaires are pages and pages of people\rquote s accounts, they just write it all down.  Giving people an opportunity to say what they think, to say what their experience is, should be an integral p}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9911662 art of most of these studies.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 But do you call them qualitative?  No?  You\rquote 
ll have a nice trial of thousands of people which has this very strong qualitative component \endash  do you call it a \'93qualitative study\'94, or do you call it a \'93quantitative study\'94?  What happens is, in the medical press, these stu
dies tend to get written up in two parts, and I\rquote 
ve done it.  I mean, we did a randomised trial of day care, but the qualitative component got written up separately, because that is how the journals organised themselves.  So in a sense you have to do it, bu
t at least you get the parallel accounts of the same study.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6309058 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
Just out of curiosity, supposing you had a huge sample that you\rquote d got lots of qualitative data as part of it, how does that get analysed?  Just coping with that volume of data?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Well, I
 think there are lots of different ways of doing it, but obviously you\rquote re not going to be doing something which is extremely labour intensive in terms of coding large amounts of text, so the method would vary.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
I want to ask you about Feminism.
