\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Liz:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
And the fact that some of the things you\rquote ve written mix, if you like, more traditional academic ways with more literary ways. I wondered what inspired you to do that?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2764307 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid5071929\charrsid5071929 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Well, I think it goes back to what I wanted to do when I was young, which is I want
ed to write fiction.  And then when those novels, early novels, got rejected, I thought, \'93Well, I\rquote ll have to go and do fact for a while.  I\rquote ll have to go and do sociology for a while\'94
, and that kind of lengthened. But then I found myself, for instance, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 Becoming a Mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
 [1979], that book uses the bold - I mean, the italics are the bits that I wrote, and the bold text is what the women said. I had a big struggle with the publisher to ensure that we reversed the fonts, because I was making a point there, that
 this is the reverse of the usual way of writing up research, which is that you put the quotes in italics, and you put the authoritative research voice in the ordinary font.  So I began, quite early on, to experiment with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid2764307 different ways of doing that.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 I think the borderline between fact and fiction is actually much more blurred than many people accept.  I
\rquote ve had some fun!  I\rquote ve [published seven] novels, and in some of those novels I use excerpts from interviews \endash  nobody\rquote s spotted it!  I use things.  I mean
, I put into the mouths of characters things that people have actually said in interviews, as I suppose a different way of making the same point, or a way of reaching a different kind of audience.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6309058 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16731643\charrsid16731643 
