So she asked me to write something.  I presumably had been talking to all and sundry, at the time, about this particular little quandary that I found myself in in doing this interviewing, and so Helen said, \'93Why don\rquote 
t you put the thoughts down in a chapter?\'94  And I think it is probably one of my most quoted and most used works, even today, which is how many years on?  Thirty-something years on, because I still get e-mails about it.  So there\rquote 
s something interesting in that, about the impact of people\rquote s work: that it isn\rquote t only necessarily the things that they themselves want to write that have an impact, but the things that other people can see are }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid2046902 interesting about their work.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 The reflections in that chapter
 very much came out of the experience of trying to do research at a time when I think a lot of social researchers had very little training.  There was very little training in research methodology then, so I hadn\rquote 
t been on courses on how to interview or on how to collect qualitative data - there was probably no such thing.  The concept of \lquote qualitative\rquote  data and \lquote qualitative\rquote  interviewing didn\rquote 
t exist then in the way it does now. Before I did the project, which was about women\rquote s experiences of becoming mother
s, I looked in the methodology textbooks for prescriptions about how to do interviews, and I was rather surprised to find this very mechanistic model of interviewing \endash 
 the interviewer was the data collector, and the interviewee was the data provider. It wa
s essentially not a social relationship. It was a relationship - it was not a relationship, it was a piece of interaction out of which the personal had to be taken, it had to be excluded. So that interviewers, rather like psychoanalysts, were not supposed
 to reveal anything about themselves, they were not supposed to answer questions. That was a particular problem for me on this project, and I thought, \'93Where does this model come from?  It really, surely, can\rquote 
t come from this particular context in which I\rquote m working at the moment, which is one about a woman \endash  social researcher \endash  interviewing women about experiences that they have in common\'94.  So that\rquote s the origin.  That\rquote 
s the origin of the chapter.
