\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 (LAUGHS)  Yes!  Okay, so I think I\rquote 
ve got a clearer sense of how the articles came out of your experience. But I also felt, from the interview, that you had distanced yourself from the idea of Feminist research because you say, later
, that you simply wanted to put women on an equal footing to men in research.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5798277 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 I don\rquote t think that I\rquote 
ve ever propounded a notion of Feminist research any more than I would propound a notion of masculinist research. But one of the things that chapter wa
s about was showing how existing practices and rules about how you do sociology, how you do social research, are actually derived from a masculine viewpoint, and are therefore not based on an inclusive view of the world.  So this is a correction, very muc
h like Chapter 1 of the book }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5798277 on housework was a correction. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 In Chapter 1 of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 The Sociology of Housework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
 I was saying that the standard view of sociology is all about male figures, but actually there were female figures as well.  So if you want a rounded view of where the subject has come from, you have to include those.  So what I\rquote 
m saying in the chapter about interviewing women is that when people are thinking about how to do interviews, these are some of the issues that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5798277 they need to take account of.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Also what I was highlighting was, I think, the discrepancy between the textbook model of interviewing and what actually happens, because I do not \endash 
 I did not and do not - believe that many people out there interviewing people about crucial life experiences, could possibly have presented themselves as interviewers in this totally mechanistic hygienic way as instruments of data collection.  That isn
\rquote t how it works.  And, indeed, people are not going to confide, they\rquote re not going to talk to you if they think you\rquote re 
not a person listening to them. On a very basic level I found it a very unreal description, not only of what was happening in my own research world, but in other people\rquote s practices of research.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6309058 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 You wrote the article in terms of women interviewing wo
men, but would the same thing apply to women interviewing men, and men interviewing men?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5798277 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Many of the same issues would apply, yes.  They\rquote 
re about how an interviewer responds when somebody that he or she is interviewing, asks a question.  For example, one of the questions I was asked in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Becoming a Mother}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902  study was, \'93Is it all right to leave a young baby alone in the house?\'94  Do you actually say, \'93Well, you should ask an expert about that\'94
, or do you give an answer?  Another one I remember is, \'93Can you avoid your baby having a cot death if you don\rquote t use a cot?\'94  \'93I\rquote m sorry, but you\rquote ve got to go and ask an expert!\'94
  And perhaps the question that most of all made me think about all this was a young woman having - well, they were all having their first 
babies, who, about three weeks before the baby was due, asked me if I could tell her which hole the baby came out of.  Mmm?  I mean, that is a reflection of the state of ante-natal [education] at the time, partly, but it wasn\rquote 
t a question to which I felt that I could say, \'93}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5798277 I\rquote m not going to answer you\'94.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
I know that people who are interviewing get asked questions: does one really respond by saying, \'93Don\rquote t ask me.  I\rquote m not really a person\'94?  So in that sense, and in other senses, these are real life issues ab
out interviewing which apply whatever the gender of the interviewer, and whatever the gender of the interviewee.   There are, though, some issues to do with, particularly, I think, at the time, which was one at which feminist ideas were quite widely discu
ssed - issues to do with sisterhood, and a woman talking to a woman about shared experiences. I think this makes the distance thing more difficult, and even, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5798277 perhaps, unethical.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 I have said there, and in other places, particularly in much of the stuff that I\rquote 
ve written about experimental methods, that I think, ultimately, there is this tension between ethics and science in a lot of research. To do what some people would regard as the ethical thing, is to deviate from canons of good scientific method, and po
ssibly vice-versa. It\rquote s a balance that we have to negotiate and think about.  It\rquote s the same for medical researchers, so it\rquote s nothing specific to social research.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6309058 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 So you continued with this approach in all the later research?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5798277 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Well, I continued 
to do interviews.  Actually, one of the outcomes of all these reflections about interviewing was a randomised trial of social support, which used the model of interviews as a way of providing social support to construct an intervention in high risk pregna
ncy. The design of that study did come directly out of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Becoming a Mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
 work, particularly out of the material I collected on how the women felt about being interviewed. Quite a lot of them said that they had found it a helpful experience.  I think that there\rquote s nothing unique about that. It\rquote 
s a common finding amongst people who do research, and who interview people. I wouldn\rquote t like to use the word \'93therapeutic\'94, but I think it is sometimes useful for people to be able to talk about themselves, and about
 critical experiences, to someone who is genuinely interested, not judgemental, and not involved. In that sense, social researchers are performing some kind of service as well as getting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5798277 
 the material that they need.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 So out of that, and out of the literatu
re on the importance of support in reducing stress in pregnancy, came the idea that an intervention consisting of supportive interviewing by midwives might have an impact on health problems amongst women. The design of the study involved women who\rquote 
d previo
usly had a small baby, so they were regarded as being at risk of having an adverse outcome in this pregnancy. We used the idea of socially supportive interviewing as the basis of the intervention.  But in the design of a randomised controlled trial, I hav
e to say that the ESRC, which was then the SSRC, absolutely didn\rquote t understand the design at all!  (LAUGHS)
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6309058 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Oh!  So was that the project they refused to support?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
Yes.  They supported the pilot study, which didn\rquote t have the randomised controlled t
rial design.  The pilot study was me going and interviewing, trying out the interviews. It was 18 months, not very big.  But then they refused to fund the main study, which was funded by the Department of Health eventually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 And what was the outcome, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
Well, the outcome was that the women who were in the group that had socially supportive interviewing did have better outcomes.  That finding was part of a general evidence base at the time, and subsequently showing that social support [was a g
ood thing]: as one of the American paediatricians involved in this research said, \'93If social support were a drug, all the pharmaceutical companies in the world would be rushing to produce it, because it\rquote s cheap and effective\'94
.  So [our study] was part of an emerging view that, actually, it\rquote s a good idea to be nice to pregnant women (LAUGHS) because it\rquote s good for them and their babies. It\rquote 
s not just an add-on luxury, but it can affect things like particularly the use of pain relief, the incidence of Caesarea
n section. So, to me, that was a very important study, and a very important outcome of thinking about interviewing and its impact on both the interviewer and the people they interviewed.  Does that make sense?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Yes, absolutely.  So with the more recent studies you\rquote 
ve done, perhaps it would be helpful if you could describe actually how the interviews were set up.  You might do some pilots, but you often}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid5798277  do most of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902  them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
Well, my most recent work, I\rquote ve been working with teams of p
eople, and most of the interviewing has not been done by me. Because one of these odd things about academic life is the older you get, and the more senior you get, the more removed you are from the ground. Which is one reason why I\rquote 
ve taken a step back from that. Anyway, we won\rquote t talk about that now, because I talked about it in the other interview.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Yes.  So do you have an interview guide, because you\rquote 
re getting other people to do the interviews?  I\rquote m wondering how you get them to do the kind of interview that you want.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2189439 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
Well in these studies, we produce the questionnaires, the interview schedules, together. Actually we are just finishing a repeat of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Becoming a Mother }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 study, which is very interesting, not least because a study done by a team 
of people is not the same as a study done by one person or two people.  I did have a researcher helping me with some of the interviews on the first study of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Becoming a Mother}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 .  [But a team effort] is a different enterprise altogether.  It\rquote s not about one person telling the others to go and do it a particular way. So we\rquote 
ve embarked on the second }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 Becoming a Mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
 study knowing that it was going to be different, because it was being done by a team of people, so there have been four or five people doing the interviews. [In this second study each woman has] been interviewed five times, but they\rquote 
ve been interviewed by the same person so that we have continuity of the interviewer across the period from early pregnancy to whe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid2189439 n the child is 18 months old.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 But there\rquote s still a team of people doing it, a team of people using the interview schedule.  And it\rquote 
s all taped, and we listen to it.  People have different styles.  I mean, they do!  (LAUGHS)  And I don\rquote t think there\rquote 
s much point in trying to standardise styles beyond a certain point.  One of the differences in this second study is that the interviews are quite a lot shorter than in the first study, and that\rquote s a reflection of a different cul
ture of research now, people perhaps having more time to sit around and be interviewed in the past. A whole lot of factors.  So the notion, as I am sure you know, the notion of a repeat study is not a simple one!  (LAUGHS)  You don\rquote 
t take the same methods and the same population and do the same study!  You attempt to address the same issues and questions in a similar way, but you have to recognise that it isn\rquote t the same.
