\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
Absolutely.  Yes.  One of the points you make in that article, is that you made friends with a third of the people you interviewed. I wondered whether you were able to carry on with making friends like that on these newer research projects?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
Well, I daresay I could have done, i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid2189439 f I\rquote d wanted to!  (LAUGHS)  But}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
 no, my ability to form those kinds of relationships and continue them, at that time, was very much influenced by where I was in my life. I had a third child to
wards the end of that project, so that was impossible to conceal!  (LAUGHS)  And that was a basis for forming a friendship beyond the end of the interviewing.
