\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid3293087 Ann:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid6309058\charrsid2046902 
Okay.  So, I mean, one of the features of the model of interviewing in the textbooks at the time was that the interviewer/interviewee relationship is essentially hierarchical, and the basic model of hierarchy is adult/child or man/woman, so you\rquote 
ve got bot
h those things going on, and certainly you have it between psychiatrists and their clients.  But what I was reflecting on, I think, was very much the value of ordinary listening, in terms of enabling people to work through experiences and to organise expe
riences in their head, so it didn\rquote t have anything to do with being influenced by a psychiatric [model] (LAUGHS)
